Online Election System
1. Introduction
The Online Election System is a web-based application designed and developed by our team as
part of our academic project. The primary objective of this project is to create a secure, efficient,
and transparent platform for conducting elections. Our team aims to provide a user-friendly
interface for voters, candidates, and administrators, while ensuring the integrity and accuracy of
the electoral process. Throughout this document, we will outline the design and development of
the Online Election System, including its functional and non-functional requirements, system
architecture, and technical specifications.
2. Product Vision
Our vision for the Online Election System is to create a reliable, accessible, and secure platform
that empowers voters, candidates, and election administrators to participate in a transparent and
efficient electoral process. We aim to make voting easier, faster, and more convenient, while
ensuring the integrity and accuracy of the election results.
3. Product Backlog
The Product Backlog consists of the following user stories and tasks:
3.1. Admin Login and Dashboard
- As an administrator, I want to be able to log in to the system securely.
- As an administrator, I want to be able to view a dashboard that displays key election metrics.
3.2. Candidate Registration and Document Verification
- As a candidate, I want to be able to register for an election online.
- As an administrator, I want to be able to verify candidate documents electronically.
3.3. Candidate Login and Profile Management
- As a candidate, I want to be able to log in to the system securely.
- As a candidate, I want to be able to view and edit my profile information.
3.4. Voter Registration and Login
- As a voter, I want to be able to register for an election online.
- As a voter, I want to be able to log in to the system securely.
3.5. Voting Mechanism and Result Calculation
- As a voter, I want to be able to cast my vote online.
- As an administrator, I want to be able to view election results in real-time.
3.6. System Security and Authentication
- As an administrator, I want to be able to ensure that the system is secure and protected from
unauthorized access.
- As a voter, I want to be able to trust that my vote is secure and confidential.
3.7. User Interface and User Experience
- As a user, I want to be able to navigate the system easily and intuitively.
- As a user, I want to be able to view clear and concise instructions and feedback.
3.8. Deployment and Maintenance
- As an administrator, I want to be able to deploy the system on a secure server.
- As an administrator, I want to be able to perform regular maintenance and updates to ensure
the system remains secure and functional.
4. Sprint Plan
The development process will be divided into 8 Sprints, each lasting 2 weeks. The Sprint plan is
as follows:
4.1. Sprint 1: Admin Login and Dashboard
- Sprint Goal: Implement Admin Login and Dashboard
- Sprint Tasks:
- Design Admin Login page
- Implement Admin Login functionality
- Create Admin Dashboard
- Integrate Admin Dashboard with database
- Visual Representations:
- Component Diagram: An Illustration of the high-level components of the Admin Login and
Dashboard
- System Context Diagram: Showing the system's interactions with external entities, like
administrators and the database
4.2. Sprint 2: Candidate Registration and Document Verification
- Sprint Goal: Implement Candidate Registration and Document Verification
- Sprint Tasks:
- Design Candidate Registration page
- Implement Candidate Registration functionality
- Integrate document verification API
- Store verified documents in database
- Visual Representations:
- Flowchart: This Depicts the steps involved in Candidate Registration and Document
Verification
- Data Flow Diagram (DFD): Illustrate the flow of data between different components of the
system
4.3. Sprint 3: Candidate Login and Profile Management
- Sprint Goal: Implement Candidate Login and Profile Management
- Sprint Tasks:
- Design Candidate Login page
- Implement Candidate Login functionality
- Create Candidate Profile page
- Integrate profile editing functionality
- Visual Representations:
- Wireframes or Mockups: An interactive illustration of the Candidate Login and Profile
Management UI
4.4. Sprint 4: Voter Registration and Login
- Sprint Goal: Implement Voter Registration and Login
- Sprint Tasks:
- Design Voter Registration page
- Implement Voter Registration functionality
- Integrate login functionality
- Store voter information in database
- Visual Representations:
- Use Case Diagram: Illustrate the interactions between voters and the system
- Sequence Diagram: Show the sequence of events involved in Voter Registration and Login
4.5. Sprint 5: Voting Mechanism and Result Calculation
- Sprint Goal: Implement Voting Mechanism and Result Calculation
- Sprint Tasks:
- Design Voting page
- Implement Voting functionality
- Integrate result calculation algorithm
- Display election results
- Visual Representations:
- State Machine Diagram: Illustrate the different states of the voting process
- Activity Diagram: Show the activities involved in the voting process and result calculation
4.6. Sprint 6: System Security and Authentication
- Sprint Goal: Implement System Security and Authentication
- Sprint Tasks:
- Implement secure authentication and authorization
- Integrate encryption for sensitive data
- Conduct regular security audits
- Visual Representations:
- Security Architecture Diagram: Illustrate the security measures implemented in the system
- Threat Model Diagram: Identify potential security threats and vulnerabilities in the system
4.7. Sprint 7: User Interface and User Experience
- Sprint Goal: Improve User Interface and User Experience
- Sprint Tasks:
- Design user-friendly interface for all users
- Conduct usability testing and gather feedback
- Iterate on design improvements
- Visual Representations:
- Wireframes and Mockups: Sketches of the system's UI
4.8. Sprint 8: Deployment and Maintenance
- Sprint Goal: Deploy and Maintain the System
- Sprint Tasks:
- Deploy application on secure server
- Conduct regular backups and updates
- Monitor system performance and address issues
- Visual Representations:
- Deployment Diagram: An illustration of deployment architecture of the system
- System Monitoring Diagram: An illustration to Show the system monitoring and maintenance
processes
5. Technical Requirements
- Front-end: HTML5, CSS3, JavaScript, ReactJS
- Back-end: NodeJS, ExpressJS, MongoDB
- Database: MongoDB
- Security: OAuth, SSL/TLS, Encryption
- Deployment: AWS, Docker
6. Testing and Quality Assurance
To ensure our Online Election System is reliable, secure, and works as expected, we'll perform the
following tests:
Unit Testing: We'll use Jest to test individual components and functions, making sure each part
works correctly.
Integration Testing: Cypress will help us test how different components interact, ensuring the
system works seamlessly from start to finish.
User Acceptance Testing (UAT): We'll conduct UAT to confirm the system meets stakeholders'
requirements and expectations, gathering feedback and making necessary adjustments.
Code Review: Regular code reviews will ensure our code is readable, maintainable, and follows
best practices, guaranteeing security and vulnerability-free code.
7. Conclusion
In conclusion, the Online Election System is a secure and efficient web-based application that
promotes transparency and accountability in the electoral process. Its adaptable and scalable design
ensures the integrity of future elections.
